// ch05 §5.16 / spec 01-unsafe §5.2(3.1)/(3.2): only a bodyless
// extern "C" declaration's address is unsafe-qualified. An extern "C"
// function *with* a body is not covered by that exception, so taking
// its address yields an ordinary, not-unsafe-qualified function
// pointer. Directly naming the function in a call is still an
// extern-"C" call and therefore gated by ch05 §5.5; this case tests
// the separate pointer-type-selection rule only.
extern "C" int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}

int main() {
    int (*fp)(int, int) = add;
    return fp(4, 7);
}
